If you come to Scala from Java, the first thing you will go looking for is the static keyword. You will not find it. Scala has no statics at all. Instead it gives you something cleaner and more consistent: the object. And once you understand objects, companions fall right out of them.

Start with a plain object. Write object Logger, and inside it put a var level and a def log. What you have just declared is a singleton. There is exactly one Logger in the whole program, it is created lazily the first time you touch it, and you call its members straight on the name: Logger dot log of a message. No instances, no new, no factory. One object, always there when you need it.

This is where everything that would have been static goes. Module-level state, utility functions, constants, configuration, an application's entry point: in Scala they all live inside an object. So instead of a special static modifier bolted onto classes, you have an ordinary object that happens to hold those members. It is the same language feature you already know, used for one more job. One concept instead of two.

Now for the interesting part. What happens when you give an object the exact same name as a class, in the same file? Then the two become companions. The class and its companion object are bound together as a pair. They share a name, and crucially, they can see each other's private members. The class can reach into the object's privates, and the object can reach into the class's privates. They are two halves of one design.

Why is that useful? Because it gives the object a natural job: it becomes the place you construct and deconstruct the class. Look at the code. Class Cat takes a val name, and holds a private id. Right beside it, object Cat is the companion. Inside the companion you define two special methods, and Scala treats them as magic.

The first is apply. Def apply takes a name and returns new Cat of that name. The apply method is special because Scala lets you call it just by using the object's name like a function. So when you write Cat of the string Tom, with no new keyword, Scala quietly turns that into Cat dot apply of Tom. That is the factory pattern, built into the language. This is exactly why you almost never write new in Scala, and why case classes feel so light: a case class generates this apply for you automatically.

The second special method is unapply. Def unapply takes a Cat and returns an Option of its parts, here Some of the cat's name. Unapply is the reverse of apply. Where apply builds a Cat from a name, unapply takes a Cat apart back into a name. And that is precisely the hook that pattern matching uses. When you write, c match, case Cat of n, Scala calls Cat dot unapply behind the scenes, and if it returns Some, it binds n to the value inside. So apply lets you construct in a match-free way, and unapply lets you destructure inside a match. The companion object owns both ends.

Step back and see how the pieces connect. An object is a lazily-created singleton, and it is where Scala puts everything other languages would mark static. A companion is just an object that shares a class's name and its privates, which makes it the obvious home for the class's factory and extractor. Apply turns the object into a constructor you call without new. Unapply turns it into a pattern you can match against. And case classes simply hand you all of this for free, which is why they are the default way to model data.

So the next time you reach for static, remember: in Scala you reach for an object instead. And the moment that object shares a name with a class, you unlock the cleanest construction and pattern-matching story in the language.
